GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 556
Short Title: 2025 Charter Schools Review Board Omnibus. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Willis.
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Education - K-12, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 31, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REQUIRE CHARTER SCHOOLS REVIEW BOARD APPROVAL OF ALL
3 STATE RULES RELATED TO CHARTER SCHOOLS, TO AUTHORIZE THE REVIEW
4 BOARD TO HIRE LEGAL COUNCIL, TO EXEMPT CHARTER SCHOOLS FROM
5 REPORTING CLASS RANK ON STUDENT TRANSCRIPTS, TO ALLOW CHARTER
6 SCHOOLS TO USE ALTERNATE TEACHER EVALUATIONS, TO REQUIRE
7 LOW-PERFORMING CHARTERS TO REPORT IMPROVEMENT PLANS TO THE
8 REVIEW BOARD ONLY, TO ALLOW THE CHARTER SCHOOLS REVIEW BOARD
9 TO REVIEW DECISIONS RELATED TO CHARTER SCHOOL FEDERAL FUNDING,
10 TO CREATE AN EXPEDITED APPLICATION PROCESS FOR CERTAIN REMOTE
11 CHARTER ACADEMIES, AND TO HAVE REMOTE CHARTER ACADEMIES
12 GRADED SEPARATELY.
13 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
14 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 115C-218 reads as rewritten:
15 "§ 115C-218. Purpose of charter schools; role of State Board of Education; establishment
16 of North Carolina Charter Schools Review Board and North Carolina Office of
17 Charter Schools.
18 …
19 (a1) State Board of Education. – The State Board of Education shall have the following
20 duties regarding charter schools:
21 (1) Rulemaking. – To establish all rules for the operation and approval of charter
22 schools. Any rule or policy adopted by the State Board regarding charter
23 schools shall first be approved and recommended by the Charter Schools
24 Review Board.
25 (2) Funding. – To allocate funds to charter schools.
26 (3) Appeals. – To hear appeals from decisions of the Charter Schools Review
27 Board under G.S. 115C-218.9.
28 (4) Accountability. – To ensure accountability from charter schools for school
29 finances and student performance.
30 (b) North Carolina Charter Schools Review Board. –
31 …
32 (10) Powers and duties. – The Review Board shall have the following duties:
33 a. To make recommendations to the State Board of Education on the
34 adoption of propose, recommend, and approve rules and policies
35 regarding all aspects of charter school operation, including time lines,
*H556-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 processes, standards, and criteria for acceptance and approval of
2 applications, monitoring of charter schools, and grounds for
3 revocation of charters.
4 …
5 e. To review any decisions or conduct any hearings pursuant to 20 U.S.C.
6 § 1231b-2 concerning the provision, repayment, or termination of
7 funds provided to a charter school.
8 f. To contract for and employ legal counsel, including private counsel,
9 to advise, represent, and provide litigation services to the Review
10 Board, without need to obtain permission or approval pursuant to
11 G.S. 114-2.3 or G.S. 147-17.
12 …
13 (c) North Carolina Office of Charter Schools. –
14 …
15 (2) Executive Director. – The Executive Director shall report to and serve at the
16 pleasure of the Superintendent of Public Instruction Review Board at a salary
17 established by the Superintendent Review Board within the funds
18 appropriated for this purpose. The duties of the Executive Director shall
19 include presenting the recommendations and decisions of the Review Board
20 at meetings of the State Board.
21 …."
22 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 115C-218.15(c) reads as rewritten:
23 "(c) A charter school shall operate under the written charter signed by the State
24 Superintendent and the applicant. The terms of the written charter shall be approved by the
25 Review Board. A charter school is not required to enter into any other contract. The charter shall
26 incorporate the information provided in the application, as modified during the charter approval
27 process, and any terms and conditions imposed on the charter school by the Review Board, or if
28 the approval is granted through an appeal pursuant to G.S. 115C-218.9, any conditions imposed
29 by the State Board of Education. No other terms may be imposed on the charter school as a
30 condition for receipt of local funds."
31 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 115C-218.85 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
32 "(d) Notwithstanding G.S. 116-11(10a) or any other provision of law to the contrary, a
33 charter school shall not be required to list class rank on a student's official transcript or record."
34 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 115C-218.90(a) is amended by adding a new subdivision to
35 read:
36 "(7) A charter school may develop and use any evaluation for conducting
37 evaluation of teachers provided that it includes standards and criteria similar
38 to those used in the North Carolina Professional Teaching Standards and
39 North Carolina Teacher Evaluation Process, or such other evaluation standard
40 and process required to be used by local school administrative units."
41 SECTION 1.(e) G.S. 115C-218.94 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
42 "(c) The Review Board shall require charter schools that are identified as low-performing
43 or continually low-performing to prepare and report on plans to improve the performance of the
44 school. The requirements of G.S. 115C-105.27 shall not apply to charter schools."
45 SECTION 1.(f) G.S. 115C-218.105 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 115C-218.105. State and local funds for a charter school.
47 …
48 (a2) The State Board shall may withhold or reduce distribution of funds to a charter school
49 if any of the following applies:
Page 2 House Bill 556-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The change in funding is due to an annual adjustment based on enrollment or
2 is a general adjustment to allocations that is not specific to the charter or
3 actions of that charter school.
4 (2) The Review Board notifies the State Board that the charter school has
5 materially violated a term of its charter, has violated a State statute or federal
6 law, or has had its charter terminated or nonrenewed.
7 (3) The Superintendent of Public Instruction Review Board notifies the State
8 Board that the charter school has failed to meet generally accepted standards
9 of fiscal management or has violated a State or federal requirement for receipt
10 of funds.
11 …
12 (c2) The Superintendent of Public Instruction Review Board shall, in consultation with
13 charter schools and local school administrative units, create a standardized enrollment
14 verification and transfer request document that each charter school shall use to request the per
15 pupil share of the local current expense fund from the local school administrative units. Charter
16 schools shall only be required to list the name, age, grade, address, date of charter enrollment,
17 date of charter withdrawal, district of residence, and student identification number of each student
18 as provided to the charter school by the student's parent or guardian in the enrollment verification
19 and transfer request document that the charter school submits to the local school administrative
20 units. A charter school, in its discretion, may take further steps to confirm the student's residence
21 in a particular local school administrative unit.
22 (c3) The Superintendent of Public Instruction Review Board shall, in consultation with
23 charter schools and local school administrative units, create a standardized procedure that local
24 school administrative units shall use when transferring the per pupil share of the local current
25 expense fund to charter schools. The standardized procedure for transfer of the per pupil share of
26 the local current expense fund shall require, to the extent practicable, that the local school
27 administrative units make the transfers by electronic transfer.
28 …."
29 SECTION 1.(g) G.S. 115C-218.123 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
30 "(c) If a school is operating under a charter that allows for a remote academy as part of the
31 charter, and the school enrolls or intends to enroll 250 or more students in the remote academy,
32 the school may request that the Review Board grant the remote academy portion of the school a
33 separate charter by submitting the information listed under subsection (a) of this section with the
34 request. Requests submitted pursuant to this section shall be reviewed through an expedited
35 process to be established by the Review Board. The Review Board shall not require a planning
36 year for remote academies granted a charter pursuant to this section."
37 SECTION 1.(h) G.S. 115C-218.125 reads as rewritten:
38 "§ 115C-218.125. Evaluation.
39 (a) The State Board of Education shall evaluate the success of remote charter academies
40 approved under this Part. Success shall be measured by school performance scores and grades,
41 retention rates, attendance rates, and, for grades nine through 12, high school completion and
42 dropout rates. The Board shall report by November 15 of each year to the Joint Legislative
43 Education Oversight Committee on the evaluation of these academies and on any recommended
44 statutory changes.
45 (b) If a school is operating under a charter that includes in-person instruction and a remote
46 charter academy, the remote charter academy shall receive a separate school performance grade
47 and be treated as a separate school for the purposes of assessing the performance of the remote
48 charter academy pursuant to G.S. 115C-12(9)c1., 115C-83.15, 115C-218.94, and 115C-218.95."
49 SECTION 2. This act is effective when it becomes law and applies beginning with
50 the 2025-2026 school year.
